  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad international consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"), typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice is universally condemned because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud, by disguising the origins of the funds.\n\n### Key Points of Consensus:\n1. **International Agreements**:  \n   - The **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (the Vienna Convention) was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering.  \n   - The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** was established in 1989 to combat money laundering and has since set global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.  \n   - Many countries have ratified the **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (the Palermo Convention), which includes provisions against money laundering.\n\n2. **National Laws**:  \n   - Nearly all countries have enacted laws criminalizing money laundering. For example, the U.S. has the **Bank Secrecy Act (1970)** and the **Patriot Act (2001)**, while the European Union has issued multiple AML Directives.  \n   - These laws typically require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions, conduct customer due diligence, and maintain records.\n\n3. **Global Enforcement**:  \n   - Governments and regulatory bodies worldwide actively investigate and prosecute money laundering cases.  \n   - International cooperation, such as through **Interpol** and **Europol**, is essential for tackling cross-border money laundering activities.\n\n4. **Corporate Responsibility**:  \n   - Businesses, especially financial institutions, are required to implement AML compliance programs to prevent and detect money laundering. Failure to do so can result in severe penalties, including fines and reputational damage.\n\n### Exceptions and Challenges:  \nWhile the consensus against money laundering is strong, enforcement varies across jurisdictions. Some countries may have weaker AML frameworks due to limited resources, corruption, or lack of political will. Additionally, the rise of cryptocurrencies and other financial innovations has created new challenges for detecting and preventing money laundering.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is widely recognized as illegal and harmful to the global financial system, and efforts to combat it are a priority for most nations.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
